Single ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‹Å“Wild ManÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ sees a shift in gear ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ springy, exotic electronics, a sprightlier pace and a sense of playfulness as a husky-voiced Bush trades the last songÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s impossible man for another as she dreams about the possibility of a yeti. Describing a Kate Bush track without making it sound silly can be rather trying ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ this is a woman whose past triumphs include several songs featuring Rolf Harris ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ but I guess ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‹Å“Wild ManÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ works as lush, sensual dream of the possibility of the things that might existing outside humdrum human experience. ItÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s not just about the yeti, but the impossibly exotic place names she mutters in her verbal quest for the creature ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œKangchenjungaÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ Metoh-KangmiÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ Lhakpa-LaÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ Dipu MarakÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ DarjeelingÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ TengbocheÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ QinghaiÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ Himachal PradeshÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ and the vertiginously thrilling change of gear as heavily distorted guest Andy Fairweather Low roars a near indecipherable chorus. ItÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s also about BushÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s formidable production skills, her precise, nagging synths and total mastery of studio as instrument. 

Those synths imbue ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‹Å“Snowed in at Wheeler StreetÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ with a sense of frazzled foreboding that negates the potential cheesiness of Elton JohnÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s throaty turn on a duet that casts him and Bush as a pair of lovers spread across time, doomed to separate at key points in history, wishing that could return to one mundane, snow bound day spent together. And a bed of electronics whip up a quietly hypnotic tumult on the astonishing title song. Here ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ and again Kate Bush songs can be a job to not make sound ridiculous ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ Bush counts to 50 in a hushed monotone as Stephen Fry (oh yes) recites a list of names for snow, real and imagined: ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œblackbird brailleÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ stella tundraÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ vanilla swarmÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚Â¦ avalancheÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½, occasionally punctured by an eerily muted chorus in which Bush frenzied urges him to continue the list. On the one hand, it continues ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‹Å“Wild ManÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s revelry in the intoxicating power of human language. On the other, itÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s the albumÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s least human track, its churning, chiming electronics and alien words mirroring the quiet chaos and leaden intensity of a snowstorm, its final minutes a headlong descent into oblivion and whiteout. It is astonishing, immense, bizarre and perfectly realized: only Kate Bush could conceive of this song, and nobody else will make anything like it again.

As the cooing over DirectorÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s Cut demonstrated, even Bush on diversionary form is enough to tease gushy spurts of adjectives from the soberest of souls; hitting a true peak again, there is the temptation to drone on about how important she is, how she dwarfs most of her peers artistically, let alone the braying yahs and rahs of today who cite her as an influence. But letÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s keep it in perspective: in the 26 years since Hounds of Love, Aerial and 50 Words for Snow have been her only truly fully realised albums. Kate Bush is more than fallible; but at peak she is incomparable. 9/10
